equests</strong> by permitting different activities selectable from different tab sets available for these two groups of users:<br /><br /><ul><li>The main <em><strong>End User Application</strong></em> tab groups the tabs selectable by the <strong>end-users</strong>.</li><li>The main <strong><em>Workflow</em></strong> tab groups all the workflow related manipulation tabs without restriction.</li></ul><p>&nbsp; <br />The tested workflows (<strong>Applications</strong>) are stored in the common <strong>Repository</strong> (pushed there by issuing the command <strong>export</strong> in the <strong><em>Workflow/Concrete</em></strong> tab) from where the <strong>users</strong> can copy them into his/her own name space by using the <strong><em>Import</em></strong> tab.</p><p><br /><strong>Import</strong> is accessible either for the experienced users from the developer <strong><em>Workflow</em></strong> tab or for the inexperienced end-users from the <em><strong>End User Application</strong></em> tab.<br />&nbsp;&nbsp; <br />Please note that the <strong>Repository</strong> does not only stores <strong>Applications</strong>, but only <strong>Applications</strong> will appear in the list shown in this page.<br /><br /> To avoid name collisions, the names of the imported objects will be extended with a unique number.<br /><br />A <strong>user</strong> can perform five kind of activities associated by proper buttons to a selected <strong>Application</strong>:</p><ul><li><strong>Configure</strong> it with permitted input parameters</li><li>Check the correctness of the Application by <strong>Info</strong></li><li><strong>Submit</strong> the Application to execute it on a (remote) resource.</li><li>Fetch the result of the terminated Application with <strong>get Outputs</strong></li><li><strong>Delete</strong> the Application.&nbsp; </li></ul><p><br />Beyond that additional activity may be done on different <strong>Tabs</strong>: </p><p>&nbsp;</p><ul><li>to fetch a proxy Certificate by <em><strong>Certificates</strong></em>, or </li><li>to archive the executed Application with all inputs and settings by <em><strong>Storage</strong></em>&nbsp; </li></ul><p>&nbsp; <br /><strong>II.Details:</strong><br /><br /><strong>1. Configure</strong><br /><br />Hitting this <strong>button</strong> opens a new <strong>form</strong>:<br /><br />Only those <strong>parameters</strong> of the <strong>Workflow</strong> can be changed which had been chosen by the developer of the <strong>Application</strong> earlier. Technically the <strong>end-user</strong> sees the input parameters separated by lines:<br /><br />There is an <strong>obligatory label</strong> to identify the <strong>parameter</strong> before the <strong>input field</strong> by which the given <strong>input parameter</strong> can be changed or must be defined.<br />There may be <em><strong>supplementary information</strong></em> hidden by a little <strong>&quot;paper page&quot;&nbsp; - icon</strong> in the line of the <strong>parameter</strong>. Clicking on the icon, the information can be read.<br />The <strong>label</strong> and the <strong>supplementary information</strong> are defined when the <strong>experienced user</strong> creates a <strong>Template</strong> and opens a configuration parameter for the <strong>end-user</strong>.<br /><br />As a result, the <strong>end-user</strong> gets all editable parameters of a complex <strong>Application</strong> (which may include any number of embedded workflows as well) on a <strong>single page</strong>, while the <strong>experienced user</strong> using the full capacity of the system <strong>must visit</strong> the proper places in the definition hierarchy to fetch the tools (<strong>Graph Editor</strong>, <strong>Job Property</strong>, <strong>Port Property</strong> configuration) to pinpoint the editable/definable parameters through a proper &quot;keyhole&quot;.<br />&nbsp; <br />The type of an input field may be </p><ul><li><em>string</em>, </li><li><em>number</em>, </li><li><em>enumerated value</em> selectable with a <strong>radio button</strong> selector, </li><li>or a <strong>file</strong> selected by a <strong>file browser</strong>. </li></ul><p>The change have been done by the <strong>user</strong> must be confirmed with the <strong>Save on Server</strong> button. <br /><br /><strong>2. Info</strong><br /><br />The <strong>Info</strong> button helps to control the correctness of the <strong>Application</strong>.<br /><br />In the most common case the lack of a <strong>proxy certificate</strong> authorizing the <strong>user</strong> to submit the <strong>Application</strong> can be read here. <br />Using the <strong><em>Certificate</em></strong> tab, the <strong>user</strong> can download the necessary <strong>short time proxy certificates</strong> from the <strong>MyProxy</strong> server. <br />Please note that the <strong>Application</strong> may use several different destination environments (several <strong>Grids</strong> and/or <strong>Virtual Organizations</strong>) and they may need different <strong>certificates</strong> or (certificate <strong>extensions</strong>) therefore the <strong>proxy certificates</strong> must be associated with the proper <strong>Grid/VO</strong>. </p><p><strong>3. Submission</strong><br /><br />The <strong>Submit button</strong> serves the starting of the <strong>Application</strong>. <br /><br /><strong>3.1 States</strong><br /><br />This <strong>button</strong> (synchronized by the <strong>Application</strong>) has several <strong>states</strong> (and <strong>labels</strong>) and hitting the <strong>button</strong> the first time its new label will be &quot;<strong>Suspend all</strong>&quot;. By hitting the &quot;<strong>Suspend all</strong>&quot; button the <strong>Application</strong> will be suspended, and the <strong>button</strong> will be labeled as &quot;<strong>Resume</strong>&quot; with the proper consequences of hitting it, or the <strong>user</strong> can select in this state the reappearing &quot;<strong>Configuration</strong>&quot; button to abort the submission indirectly.<br /><br />The actual state of the submitted <strong>Application</strong> is rendered graphically by a text message appearing in a little box whose background color is associated to the state.<br /><br /><strong>3.2 Data</strong><br /><br />One main lesson to learn here is the following: </p><p>If your privileges are other than the <strong>experienced user</strong>&rsquo; one, (<strong><em>Workflow/Real Workflow</em></strong> tab -&gt; <em><strong>Submit</strong></em> button) there will be only a <strong>single</strong> common instance of the <strong>Application</strong> created (containing the <strong>outputs</strong> and the run time state of the <strong>workflow(s)</strong>) upon the <strong>submission</strong> of the <strong>Application</strong>. <br />The consequence is that the <strong>user</strong> should save/remember the results (and/or inputs) of the submitted Application to prevent the overwriting of it before submitting the same <strong>Application</strong> the next time.</p><p><strong>3.3. Notification</strong><br /><br />Similar to the advanced user&rsquo; privileges the <strong>end-user</strong> may receive an e-mail notification about the termination/state change of the submitted <strong>Application</strong>. </p><p>However the prerequisites of the messaging are the proper settings of the <strong><em>Notify</em></strong> tab. <br /><br /><strong>4. Fetching the results</strong><br /><br />The <strong>get Outputs</strong> button appears upon the successful termination of the <strong>Application</strong>.<br />Hitting the <strong>button</strong> the <strong>file download</strong> mechanism of the applied <strong>internet browser </strong>will be opened by which the <strong>local output files</strong> supplied by the <strong>main workflow</strong> of the <strong>Application</strong> can be downloaded. </p><p>If the user is interested in a more detailed view of the results (inputs, circumstances ) or just wants to archive the made experiment he/she can do it by downloading the <strong>Application</strong>. The download can be made within the <strong><em>Storage</em></strong> tab where it is a selectable option even for the <strong>end-user</strong>s.</p><p><strong>5. Deleting the Application </strong><br /><br />The <strong><em>Delete</em></strong> button erases the <strong>Application</strong> completely and therefore it must be handled with care. </p><p>However a deleted Application can be rebuilt from the <strong>Repository</strong>.&nbsp; <br /><br /><strong><br /> </strong></p>'),('text.job.GemlcaLegacyCode','text.job.Gemlca_Service_Method','Service Method'),('please.configure.jobio','Message_job_config_IO','Do not forget to configure the file associations in the <strong>Job Inputs and Outputs</strong> tab<br />'),('text.job.Gemlcarepo','Selected_Job_GLEMCA_Repository','GEMLCA Repository'),('text.io.gemlcaint','Selected_Port_INTERNA_FILE_NAME_GLEMCA','Internal File Name(GEMLCA)<strong> </strong>'),('text.io.gemlcaintoptional','Selected_Port_Glemva_otput_name_option','Optional name for output file<strong> </strong>'),('config.job.gemlcarepo','Config_job_gemlca_Repository_comm','A <strong>GEMLCA</strong> code works as a true service, which can be explored at the time of the configuration and will be called at run time. <br />&nbsp;<br />The found <strong>GEMLCA Repositories</strong> publish the supported services which are implemented by legacy codes running on certain hosts.<br /><br />Therefore &ndash; as a difference to the traveling code &ndash; a valid user certificate accepted by the given <strong>GEMLCA Repository</strong> must be present already in the workflow configuration phase in order to communicate with the <strong>GEMLCA Repository</strong> asking for the required services and for its parameters. <br />&nbsp;The roots of the query - the URLs of the available <strong>GEMLCA Repositories</strong> &ndash; are maintained by the <strong>Settings</strong> portlet<br /><br />&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;<br />The job configuration happens in a strict hierarchic order:<br /><br />1. At first the necessary <strong>GEMLCA Repository</strong> will be selected from the set of available resources. It will show the set of supported <strong>Service Method</strong>s.<br />'),('config.job.gemlcalc','Config_job_gemelca_Service_Method','The job configuration happens in a strict hierarchic order:<br /><br />1. At first the necessary <strong>GEMLCA Repository</strong> will be selected from the set of available resources. It will show the set of supported <strong>Service Methods</strong>.<br /><br />In the current implementation there is also a strict filtering: the <strong>gUSE</strong> will show only those <strong>Service Methods</strong> which fulfill the &ldquo;strict interface condition&rdquo; i.e. the number of <strong>input file parameters</strong> must correspond to the number of <strong>input ports</strong> of the enveloping <strong>job</strong>, and the number of the <strong>output file parameters</strong> must correspond to the number of the <strong>output ports</strong> of the enveloping <strong>job</strong>.<br /><br />2. By selecting one of the available <strong>Service Methods</strong> two things happen:<br /><br />&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 3.1 A form - labeled as &ldquo;<strong>GEMLCA parameters</strong>&rdquo; - will open encountering the list of names and re-definable default values of the &ndash; <strong>non file</strong> like - input parameters of the selected <strong>Service Method</strong> and <br />&bull;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 3.2 a list labeled as &ldquo;<strong>Resource/Broker</strong>&rdquo; will encounter the sites where proper legacy code has been placed which may implement the execution of the selected <strong>Service Method</strong>. A distinguished element of the resource list may be the wildcard &ldquo;<strong>broker</strong>&rdquo; indicating that - if selected - the backend system will decide about the chosen resource.<br /><br /><!--[if gte mso 9]><xml>  <w:WordDocument>   <w:View>Normal</w:View>   <w:Zoom>0</w:Zoom>   <w:Compatibility>    <w:BreakWrappedTables/>    <w:SnapToGridInCell/>    <w:WrapTextWithPunct/>    <w:UseAsianBreakRules/>   </w:Compatibility>   <w:BrowserLevel>MicrosoftInternetExplorer4</w:BrowserLevel>  </w:WordDocument> </xml><![endif]--> <!--  /* Font Definitions */  @font-face 	{font-family:Wingdings; 	panose-1:5 0 0 0 0 0 0 0 0 0; 	mso-font-charset:2; 	mso-generic-font-family:auto; 	mso-font-pitch:variable; 	mso-font-signature:0 268435456 0 0 -2147483648 0;}  /* Style Definitions */  p.MsoNormal, li.MsoNormal, div.MsoNormal 	{mso-style-parent:\"\"; 	margin:0in; 	margin-bottom:.0001pt; 	mso-pagination:widow-orphan; 	font-size:12.0pt; 	font-family:\"Times New Roman\"; 	mso-fareast-font-family:\"Times New Roman\";} @page Section1 	{size:8.5in 11.0in; 	margin:1.0in 1.25in 1.0in 1.25in; 	mso-header-margin:.5in; 	mso-footer-margin:.5in; 	mso-paper-source:0;} div.Section1 	{page:Section1;}  /* List Definitions */  @list l0 	{mso-list-id:1949922528; 	mso-list-type:hybrid; 	mso-list-template-ids:-85672676 67698689 67698691 67698693 67698689 67698691 67698693 67698689 67698691 67698693;} @list l0:level1 	{mso-level-number-format:bullet; 	mso-level-text:?; 	mso-level-tab-stop:1.0in; 	mso-level-number-position:left; 	margin-left:1.0in; 	text-indent:-.25in; 	font-family:Symbol;} ol 	{margin-bottom:0in;} ul 	{margin-bottom:0in;} -->Ãƒâ€šÃ‚Â '),('config.job.gemlcaresource','Config_job_gemlca_resourec_comm','<strong>S</strong>electing one of the available <strong>Service Methods</strong> the list labeled as &ldquo;<strong>Resource/Broker</strong>&rdquo; will encounter the sites where proper legacy code has been placed which may implement the execution of the selected <strong>Service Method</strong>. A distinguished element of the resource list may be the wildcard &